Worldwide plan for renewal of lighting
Last yesterday, the UN proposed a plan for renewal of the lighting of households, trade and industry in 100 countries in order to achieve a reduction in greenhouse gas (FCKW) which corresponds to nearly a third of the additional reduction that needs to be achieved in order to stabilise the soil climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its position in the steps of the concrete major projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun to compensate for the absence of compulsory reduction obligations of industrial countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, the main problem would be avoided in the form of 1,8 billion tonnes (Gt) of the FCKWs released on earth, if the white-glow bears, which are still a monopoly of 50 to 70% on the market, would be replaced by fluorescent or better by light diodes (LED).
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to a equivalent of 70% of the exhaust gases of the global driving park.
Last year in Copenhagen, the large emissions centres such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, had committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans that should swallow down global FCKW emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, it is necessary to withdraw 5 Gt from this balance to stabilise the climate increase by 2 degrees Celsius from today to 2020 in order to prevent it from being uncontrolled.
In the white-glowing pears 95% of the energy is exhausted in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce light.
With the compact lighting bears, energy consumption decreases by 75%, with the new LED glue bears, this energy requirement is once again reduced by double.
The compact fluorescent bears hold between 6000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED-glow bears, such as those that the producer Philips marketed this week - this society has also participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and spend 80% less energy than a white-glow bear, which means an indication of the saving opportunities of the exchange plan to be used in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that this completely new kind of glue bears gives very little heat, they can also function with a rule resistance.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several specialists have shown that compact fluorescent bears have reserves, as they contain mercury and that they must be disposed of as a special waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, except for the producers offering an asset.
However, the main source of mercury releases on the planet, according to the report, does not represent the compact lighting bears, but rather the carbon power plants that have much more mercury to produce the electricity wasted by the white-glow bears.
In the United States alone, these carbon power plants eject 25,000 tonnes of mercury annually.
The report details the profits each country would gain thanks to this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save a billion dollars a year in purchasing electricity and eight million tonnes of CO2, which means an equivalent of 3.5 carbon power plants whose construction would cost Indonesia 2.5 billion.
